It would be reasonable to hypothesize that these peaks coincide with the winter months when demand for such merchandise would be higher. Similarly, the troughs or the lowest points in the sales data appear to happen with a regular frequency and are likely aligned with the off-season for winter sports, such as the summer months. Overall, the seasonality pattern indicated by the sales data suggests that there are certain times of the year with significantly higher sales, which for a winter sports company, are likely during the colder months when activities like skiing and ice skating are popular.")

3. g) Explain what causes the conflicting results in parts e and f above. In other words, why is the statistical significance conflicting between the individual t-test and the Partial F-test? Which model would you settle with?

print("Interpretation of conflicting results between the t-tests and the Partial F-test can be complex. The t-test assesses each coefficient's significance individually, while the Partial F-test assesses the significance of a group of variables. A variable may not be significant when tested alone but may contribute significantly to a model when combined with other variables, especially in the presence of interaction effects.

The choice of which model to settle with depends on the research question and the theoretical justification. If we are specifically interested in whether the salary difference between genders varies with education, the model with the interaction term would be more appropriate, however if we want to find individual effect toward our dependent variable, we might settle with the first model.")

The variables include X1 = number of machines to be repaired (NUMBER), X2 = years of experience of service person (EXPER), and Y = time taken (in minutes) to provide service (TIME). Develop a polynomial regression model to predict average time on the service calls using EXPER and NUMBER as explanatory variables. Justify your model choice including transformations of any variables.

CompRepair <- read_excel("CompRepair.xlsx")
plot(CompRepair$TIME, CompRepair$NUMBER, 
     main = "Average Time and Number of Machines", xlab = "NUMBER", 
     ylab = "Average Time", pch=16)
abline(lm(CompRepair$TIME ~ CompRepair$NUMBER), col = "red")
lines(lowess(CompRepair$TIME, CompRepair$NUMBER), col="blue") ## lowess = Locally weighted Scatterplot Smoothing

# OR
scatter.smooth(x=CompRepair$NUMBER, y=CompRepair$TIME, 
               main="Number of Machines~Average Time")  # scatterplot

plot(CompRepair$EXPER, CompRepair$TIME)

plot(CompRepair$NUMBER, CompRepair$TIME)

## Linear model
model1 <- lm(TIME ~ NUMBER + EXPER, data = CompRepair )

## Adding polynomial terms
model2 <- lm(TIME ~ NUMBER + I(NUMBER^2) + EXPER + I(EXPER^2), data = CompRepair )

## Adding interaction term
model3 <- lm(TIME ~ NUMBER + EXPER + NUMBER * EXPER, data = CompRepair )

# Compare models
anova(model1, model2, model3)
